1. What is the purpose of HTML in web development?
    HTML is used to create the structure and content of web pages. It defines elements such as headings, paragraphs, images, links, and forms.
2. Explain the difference between semantic and non-semantic HTML tags.
    Semantic tags describe the meaning of content (e.g., <header>, <footer>), while non-semantic tags (<div>, <span>) do not provide information about the content.
3. What is the Document Object Model (DOM)?
    The DOM is a tree-like representation of an HTML document that allows JavaScript to access and modify page elements dynamically.
4. What is the difference between <div> and <span> elements?
    <div> is a block-level element, while <span> is an inline element used within a line of text.
5. Explain the purpose of the <form> element.
    The <form> element is used to collect user input and send data to a server.
6. What are HTML attributes? Give examples.
    Attributes provide additional information about HTML elements. Examples include id, class, href, and src.
7. Explain the difference between absolute and relative URLs.
    An absolute URL contains the full web address, while a relative URL specifies a path relative to the current page.
8. What is the purpose of the <meta> tag?
    The <meta> tag provides information about the webpage, such as character encoding and page description.
9. What are HTML5 semantic elements and why are they important?
    Semantic elements describe the purpose of content and improve accessibility and SEO.
10. Explain the difference between GET and POST methods.
    GET sends data through the URL, while POST sends data in the request body.
11. What is CSS and how is it applied to a webpage?
    CSS is used to style web pages. It can be applied inline, internally, or through external files.
12. Explain the CSS box model.
    The CSS box model consists of content, padding, border, and margin.
13. What is the difference between margin and padding?
    Margin creates space outside an element, while padding creates space inside the element.
14. Explain CSS specificity.
    Specificity determines which CSS rule is applied when multiple rules target the same element.
15. What is the difference between class selectors and ID selectors?
    Classes can be used multiple times, while IDs should be unique on a page.
16. What are pseudo-classes in CSS?
    Pseudo-classes define special states of elements, such as :hover and :focus.
17. What are pseudo-elements in CSS?
    Pseudo-elements style specific parts of an element, such as ::before and ::after.
18. Explain the purpose of the position property.
    The position property controls how elements are placed on a webpage.
19. What is the difference between relative, absolute, fixed, and sticky positioning?
    Relative positions an element from its normal place, absolute positions it relative to a parent, fixed stays on screen while scrolling, and sticky switches between relative and fixed behavior.
20. Explain how Flexbox works.
    Flexbox is a layout system that helps align and distribute items inside a container.
21. What are the main properties of a Flex container?
    Common properties include flex-direction, justify-content, align-items, flex-wrap, and gap.
22. Explain CSS Grid and its advantages.
    CSS Grid is a two-dimensional layout system that makes creating complex layouts easier.
23. What are media queries and why are they used?
    Media queries apply different styles based on screen size or device characteristics.
24. What is responsive web design?
    Responsive web design ensures websites work well on different screen sizes and devices.
25. Explain the difference between display: none and visibility: hidden.
    display:none removes the element completely, while visibility:hidden hides it but keeps its space.
26. What is the purpose of CSS transitions?
    Transitions create smooth changes between CSS property values.
27. What is the purpose of CSS animations?
    Animations allow elements to move or change styles over time.
28. Explain the z-index property.
    z-index controls the stacking order of overlapping elements.
29. What is Bootstrap and why is it used?
    Bootstrap is a popular framework that provides ready-made responsive design components.
30. Explain accessibility in web development.
    Accessibility ensures websites can be used by people with disabilities.
31. What is JavaScript and where is it executed?
    JavaScript is a programming language for web interactivity. It runs in browsers and on servers.
32. Explain the difference between let, const, and var.
    let allows reassignment, const creates constants, and var is the older variable declaration method.
33. What are JavaScript data types?
    String, Number, Boolean, Undefined, Null, Object, BigInt, and Symbol.
34. Explain type conversion in JavaScript.
    Type conversion changes a value from one data type to another.
35. What is the difference between == and ===?
    == compares values with type conversion, while === compares both value and type.
36. Explain logical operators in JavaScript.
    The main logical operators are && (AND), || (OR), and ! (NOT).
37. What are conditional statements?
    Conditional statements execute different code depending on whether a condition is true or false.
38. Explain the purpose of loops in JavaScript.
    Loops repeat a block of code multiple times.
39. Compare for, while, and do…while loops.
    for is used when the number of iterations is known, while runs while a condition is true, and do...while runs at least once.
40. What are functions in JavaScript?
    Functions are reusable blocks of code designed to perform specific tasks.
41. Explain the concept of scope.
    Scope determines where variables can be accessed in a program.
42. What is the difference between local and global variables?
    Local variables exist within a function or block, while global variables are accessible throughout the program.
43. What are arrow functions?
    Arrow functions are a shorter syntax for writing functions using =>.
44. Explain function parameters and return values.
    Parameters are inputs to a function, and return values are outputs from a function.
45. What are arrays in JavaScript?
    Arrays are used to store multiple values in a single variable.
46. Explain common array methods.
    Examples include push(), pop(), shift(), unshift(), map(), and filter().
47. What are JavaScript objects?
    Objects store data as key-value pairs.
48. Explain the difference between arrays and objects.
    Arrays use indexes, while objects use named keys.
49. What is JSON and why is it used?
    JSON is a lightweight data format used for storing and exchanging information.
50. Explain event handling in JavaScript.
    Event handling allows JavaScript to respond to user actions like clicks and key presses.
51. What is an event listener?
    An event listener waits for a specific event and executes code when the event occurs.
52. Explain event bubbling.
    Event bubbling is the process where events move from a child element to its parent elements.
53. What is DOM manipulation?
    DOM manipulation involves modifying HTML elements using JavaScript.
54. Explain the difference between innerHTML and textContent.
    innerHTML handles HTML content, while textContent handles only plain text.
55. What is form validation?
    Form validation checks whether user input meets required conditions.
56. Explain client-side validation and server-side validation.
    Client-side validation occurs in the browser, while server-side validation occurs on the server.
57. What is localStorage?
    localStorage stores data in the browser until it is manually removed.
58. What is sessionStorage?
    sessionStorage stores data only during the current browser session.
59. What is asynchronous programming?
    Asynchronous programming allows tasks to run without blocking other operations.
60. Explain callbacks in JavaScript.
    A callback is a function passed to another function and executed later.
61. What is a Promise?
    A Promise represents the future result of an asynchronous operation.
62. Explain async/await.
    async/await provides a cleaner way to work with asynchronous code and Promises.
63. What is an API?
    An API allows different software applications to communicate and exchange data.
64. What is the Fetch API?
    The Fetch API is used to send HTTP requests and receive data from servers.
65. Explain HTTP status codes.
    HTTP status codes indicate the result of a request, such as 200 (Success) or 404 (Not Found).
66. What is the difference between frontend and backend development?
    Frontend focuses on the user interface, while backend handles server-side logic and databases.
67. Explain the concept of Single Page Applications (SPA).
    An SPA loads one page and updates content dynamically without reloading the entire page.
68. What are the main advantages of modular JavaScript?
    Modular JavaScript improves code organization, reusability, maintenance, and collaboration.
69. What is Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)?
    XSS is a security vulnerability where attackers inject malicious scripts into web pages.
70. Explain the importance of website performance optimization.
    Performance optimization improves loading speed, user experience, SEO rankings, and overall website efficiency.
